{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_017ncX8fu9PuujNgpYYx3RNF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is a test plan generation task for a content moderation system. The user wants me to identify the minimum testing level needed to catch real failures for 6 behaviors. Let me work through each one systematically.\n\n## Behavior 1: An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.\n\n**Analysis:**\n- Core requirement: When the vision model classifies an image as explicit → flag it, don't publish\n- Dependencies: \n  - The AI vision model (this is real LLM/ML)\n  - The flagging mechanism (probably a database or queue)\n  - The publish gate (probably a database operation or message broker)\n\n**Key questions:**\n- **MOCK-MISS**: If I mock the vision model to return \"explicit\", would I catch the failure? Partially — a mock would catch if the code fails to *read* the classification correctly, but not if:\n  - The real model fails to detect explicit content\n  - The model returns something unexpected (different schema, different confidence scores)\n  - Edge cases with the real model (encoding issues, etc.)\n- **REAL-INFRA**: Do I need real DB/filesystem? Probably yes to verify the post isn't actually published.\n- **LLM-DEP**: Yes — correctness depends on what the real AI vision model produces. The test should use a real explicit image and verify the real model flags it.\n- **MOCK-HIDE**: Mocking the model would hide failures where the real model doesn't actually detect the explicit content.\n\n**Minimum level**: Agentic (requires real AI vision model to verify it actually classifies the image correctly)\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The behavior is \"An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.\"\n\nThis has two parts:\n1. The AI model classifies it as explicit\n2. The system responds correctly to that classification\n\nFor part 2, I could mock the AI model. But for part 1, I need the real model to actually identify the image as explicit. So the full behavior requires Agentic level.\n\n\nThe real question is what failure we're trying to catch. If it's whether the system properly respects the model's classification, Integration with a mock would work. But the behavior description implies the real model should detect the content, so we need the actual model running. The key failure modes are: the code doesn't call the vision model correctly, doesn't handle its response properly, or the real model itself fails to detect the explicit content. Only Agentic testing catches that last one.\n\nFor the second behavior about hate speech and obfuscation, the core test is whether the actual model can see through evasion techniques. Mocking the model would hide whether it truly handles obfuscated examples — different models have different robustness here. The real model's behavior is what matters, so we need to test with actual obfuscated hate speech and the real classifier.\n\nFor the third behavior, I need to verify that clean posts actually get published rather than held or dropped. Mocking both models to return \"clean\" would catch if the code incorrectly holds a passing post, but might miss silent failures where posts disappear. I also want to confirm the publish operation actually succeeds, not just that the code intends to publish it. The models themselves aren't really a dependency here — the key is testing the actual publish mechanism and post flow.\n\nFor the fourth behavior, I'm looking at a performance requirement where the moderation pipeline needs to complete within 5 seconds of submission.\n\nThe core issue is that mocking the AI models would hide their actual latency—the vision and text models take real time to respond. If I mock them with instant returns, I'd miss a significant portion of the total execution time. The requirement is inherently tied to real API performance, so I need to call the actual endpoints to get meaningful results. This pushes the test to at least System level, possibly higher if the timing is truly dependent on the AI service's behavior. The distinction matters: if \"5 seconds\" includes network latency and model inference, I need real components; if it's just the orchestration logic, Integration might suffice. But for a realistic moderation pipeline, the end-to-end timing almost certainly includes the actual model calls. be considered Agentic. But the minimum to catch \"the pipeline is too slow\" would be System.\n\nI'll go with System since real network calls and infrastructure are essential, though I should note the AI model's non-deterministic latency as an Agentic consideration.\n\nFor the vision model unavailability scenario, I need to verify the post enters a retry queue rather than getting auto-approved. This requires checking both the queue state and the publish status, so Integration testing is the minimum level. Mocking the model failure alone won't suffice—I need to confirm the actual queueing behavior and that auto-approval doesn't occur.\n\nRegarding consistency across multiple submissions of the same borderline image, mocking the model masks the real issue: borderline images may produce different classifications on successive runs. If I mock it to always return the same result, I can't detect whether the actual model exhibits this inconsistency.\n\nWith the real model, I'd need to verify either that it's deterministic for this particular image, or that the system caches decisions so the same result is returned regardless. The caching strategy matters here—if the system is designed to cache moderation decisions, I can test that with a mock model. But if there's no caching, I need the real model to confirm it behaves consistently.\n\nThis is an agentic-level behavior because it depends on understanding both the model's actual behavior and the system's caching implementation. I need the real model to determine what's actually happening. I write.\n\nLet me start writing the response:\n\n## Behavior 1: Image with explicit content is flagged and held for review\n\n- **Minimum level**: Agentic\n- **Test description**: Submit a real image containing explicit content to the moderation pipeline. Verify that the AI vision model classifies it as \"explicit\" and the system holds it in a review queue instead of publishing it.\n- **Justification**: The failure mode is \"the real AI vision model fails to detect explicit content\", which requires calling the real model with real content. A mocked model would always return \"explicit\", hiding real detection failures. Mocking would also miss encoding/format issues or model API failures.\n- **Plan consistent**: Yes. To verify explicit content is actually detected, need real model (Agentic). Cannot be tested at Integration level because Integration would mock the model, missing detection failures.\n- **Level probabilities**: \n  - Unit: 0.0 (requires model call)\n  - Integration: 0.1 (mock model would hide detection failures)\n  - System: 0.1 (needs real model call; system-level infra for publish mechanism is secondary)\n  - Agentic: 0.75 (real model needed to verify detection)\n  - Workflow: 0.05 (not a multi-step pipeline issue)\n\nThe core question is whether I can catch actual failures at a lower level. There are two distinct failure modes here: the vision model itself failing to detect explicit content, and the system not responding appropriately to the model's classification. The first requires calling the actual model with real images—something only possible at Agentic level. The second could theoretically be tested at Integration with mocks, but that assumes the model works correctly, which is a significant assumption to make.\n\nIf the question asks for the minimum infrastructure to catch *any* real failure, Integration could catch response logic failures. But the most probable failure—the model missing explicit content—demands Agentic testing. For behavior 1 specifically, the real risks are the model not detecting content, the system failing to mark flagged posts, or the system publishing despite a flag. Integration testing can catch the latter two, but only Agentic testing catches the first.\n\nThe core tension is whether we're testing \"the system's response to model output\" (Integration) or \"whether the model actually detects content\" (Agentic). Given the prompt's focus on catching real failures, not just happy-path logic, Agentic seems necessary since detection failures are the most likely failure mode. Assigning rough probabilities: Unit can't test this in isolation, Integration catches some failures but misses detection issues, System testing adds infrastructure but doesn't address the core problem, Agentic is required for actual model detection testing, and Workflow isn't relevant for a single-step behavior. Good, those probabilities sum correctly. Now for behavior 2 about hate speech detection with obfuscation—the core issue is whether the actual model can see through letter substitution and unicode tricks, which absolutely requires the real model to test. A mock would always pass, masking the actual vulnerability. The probabilities reflect this: unit testing can't help (0.0), integration testing with mocks is nearly useless (0.05), system and workflow levels don't address the model's evasion resistance (0.05 each), but agentic testing with the real model is essential (0.85).\n\nFor behavior 3, I'm looking at a different kind of test—one where clean content should flow through to publication without being held or dropped. Here the AI models can be mocked since I'm really checking the orchestration logic and whether the publish operation actually executes. The failure modes are routing errors or silent failures in the pipeline, not model accuracy issues. This is integration-level work because I need to verify the full publish path works correctly when given clean classifications.\n\nFor behavior 4, I need to measure the actual end-to-end latency of the pipeline. This requires real AI model calls since I'm testing performance characteristics under realistic conditions, not just logic flow. I'm checking that submissions move from entry to a final decision within 5 seconds, which means I need to see how the system actually performs with real service dependencies.\n\nFor behavior 5, the thinking appears to be cut off. I need the next thinking to continue rewriting. of queueing requires real infrastructure. The level probabilities reflect this: unit testing can't verify actual queue writes (0.0), integration testing with mocked failures and real queue access is most appropriate (0.8), system testing with a genuinely unavailable service is possible but unnecessary (0.1), and agentic/workflow levels don't apply since this tests a specific error path rather than model behavior or multi-step orchestration (0.05 each).\n\nFor borderline image consistency, I need to test whether moderation decisions remain stable across multiple submissions of the same ambiguous image. This requires agentic-level testing because the model's behavior itself—whether it's deterministic or uses caching—is what's being validated. The test submits a borderline image several times in quick succession and confirms the decision stays consistent, either because the underlying model is deterministic or because the system caches results.\n\nThe failure mode here is inconsistent moderation due to model non-determinism, which only surfaces with real model calls. Mocks always return identical results and mask actual variance. I need the real vision model to measure whether consistency comes from the model itself or from caching logic. Unit testing can't access the model (0.0), integration testing with mocks misses real variance (0.1), system testing addresses infrastructure but not the core consistency question (0.1), agentic testing with the real model is the right fit (0.75), and workflow testing doesn't apply to a single behavior (0.05).\n\nReviewing the six behaviors: explicit content detection, hate speech despite obfuscation, and borderline consistency all require agentic-level testing with the real model. Clean post publishing and pipeline latency fit integration and system levels respectively. Model unavailability queuing works at integration level. All probability distributions sum to 1.0 and the test plans align with their required levels.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13317,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13317},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"68d4a528-2066-465f-acf2-92fe8e1ae09f","uuid":"07446c39-c7f5-4d20-bec6-56b338d38b14"}
